>
> — The Philos Project (@philosproject) [24 March
> 2017](https://twitter.com/philosproject/status/845279213951369216)

Once a city that captured the heart of every historian and archeologist,
Palmyra now evokes a sense of mourning for a rich heritage cast aside.

### **Khalid ibn al-Walid Mosque**

![](https://globalvoices.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/Khalid_ibn_al-
Walid_Mosque.jpg)

The picturesque mosque in 2005. Photo by Abdulhadi Najjar via
[Wikimedia](https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Khalid_ibn_al-
Walid_Mosque.jpg). CC BY-SA 3.0

The Khalid ibn al-Walid Mosque in Homs is named after the Muslim Arab military
commander who led the 7th century Muslim conquest of Syria that ended
Byzantine rule in the country. Consecrated in 1908, the mosque is notable for
its traditional Ottoman-Turkish architectural style.

In 2013, Assad’s forces shelled the historic mosque, ultimately destroying its
[mausoleum](http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=60268). The mosque
has witnessed regular attacks ever since.

